[src:container-registry/containers-images] In older versions of Kubernetes, the kubelet had a direct integration with cloud provider credentials.
[src:container-registry/containers-images] This provided the ability to dynamically fetch credentials for image registries.
[src:container-registry/containers-images] There were three built-in implementations of the kubelet credential provider integration: ACR (Azure Container Registry), ECR (Elastic Container Registry), and GCR (Google Container Registry).
[src:container-registry/distribution-about] A registry is a storage and content delivery system, holding named container images and other content, available in different tagged versions.
[src:container-registry/distribution-about] Users interact with a registry by pushing and pulling images.
[src:container-registry/distribution-about] The default storage driver is the local posix filesystem, which is suitable for development or small deployments.
[src:container-registry/distribution-about] Additional cloud-based storage drivers like S3, Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud Storage are supported.
[src:container-registry/distribution-about] People looking into using other storage drivers should consider if the driver they’d like to be supported is S3 compatible like many cloud storage systems as adding new storage driver support has been put on hold for the time being.
[src:container-registry/distribution-about] Since securing access to your hosted images is paramount, the Registry natively supports TLS and basic authentication.
[src:container-registry/distribution-about] The Registry GitHub repository includes additional information about advanced authentication and authorization methods.
[src:container-registry/distribution-about] Only very large or public deployments are expected to extend the Registry in this way.
[src:container-registry/distribution-about] Finally, the Registry ships with a robust notification system, calling webhooks in response to activity, and both extensive logging and reporting, mostly useful for large installations that want to collect metrics.
[src:container-registry/distribution-about] You can find out more about the various Docker commands dealing with images in the Docker engine documentation.
[src:container-registry/distribution-about] Running your own Registry is a great solution to integrate with and complement your CI/CD system.
[src:container-registry/distribution-about] In a typical workflow, a commit to your source revision control system would trigger a build on your CI system, which would then push a new image to your Registry if the build is successful.
[src:container-registry/distribution-about] A notification from the Registry would then trigger a deployment on a staging environment, or notify other systems that a new image is available.
[src:container-registry/distribution-about] It’s also an essential component if you want to quickly deploy a new image over a large cluster of machines.
[src:container-registry/distribution-about] Finally, it’s the best way to distribute images inside an isolated network.
[src:container-registry/distribution-about] You absolutely need to be familiar with Docker, specifically with regard to pushing and pulling images.
[src:container-registry/distribution-about] You must understand the difference between the daemon and the cli, and at least grasp basic concepts about networking.
[src:container-registry/distribution-about] Also, while just starting a registry is fairly easy, operating it in a production environment requires operational skills, just like any other service.
[src:container-registry/distribution-about] You are expected to be familiar with systems availability and scalability, logging and log processing, systems monitoring, and security 101.
[src:container-registry/distribution-about] Strong understanding of http and overall network communications, plus familiarity with golang are certainly useful as well for advanced operations or hacking.
[src:container-registry/distribution] The Registry is a stateless, highly scalable server side application that stores and lets you distribute container images and other content.
[src:container-registry/distribution] The Registry is open-source, under the permissive Apache license.
[src:container-registry/distribution] Users looking for a zero maintenance, ready-to-go solution are encouraged to use one of the existing registry services.
[src:container-registry/distribution] Many of these provide support and security scanning, and are free for public repositories.
[src:container-registry/distribution] Cloud infrastructure providers such as AWS, Azure, Google Cloud and IBM Cloud also have container registry services available at a cost.
[src:container-registry/distribution] The distribution registry implements the OCI Distribution Spec version 1.0.1.
[src:container-registry/distribution] You should now read the detailed introduction about the registry, or jump directly to deployment instructions.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] The core software that runs and manages these containers is called **Docker Engine**.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] Docker was first released in 2013 and continues to be developed by Docker, Inc.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] The platform includes both free and paid tiers.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] Solomon Hykes started the Docker project in France as an internal project within dotCloud, a platform-as-a-service company.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] dotCloud Inc. was founded by Kamel Founadi, Hykes, and Sebastien Pahl during the Y Combinator Summer 2010 startup incubator group and launched in 2011, and renamed to Docker Inc in 2013.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] Docker debuted to the public in Santa Clara at PyCon in 2013.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] It was released as open-source in March 2013.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] At the time, it used LXC as its default execution environment.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] One year later, with the release of version 0.9, Docker replaced LXC with its own component, *libcontainer*, which was written in the Go programming language.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] In 2017, Docker created the Moby project for open research and development.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] In March 2026, the Communications of the ACM featured Docker as the cover article in a retrospective article of the past decade.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] Containers are isolated from one another and bundle their own software, libraries and configuration files; they can communicate with each other through well-defined channels.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] Because all of the containers share the services of a single operating system kernel, they use fewer resources than virtual machines.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] Docker can package an application and its dependencies in a virtual container that can, in principle, run on any Linux, Windows, or macOS computer.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] This enables the application to run in a variety of locations, such as on-premises, in public *(see decentralized computing, distributed computing, and cloud computing)* or private cloud.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] Docker on macOS uses a Linux virtual machine to run the containers.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] Because Docker containers are lightweight, a single server or virtual machine can run several containers simultaneously.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] A 2018 analysis found that a typical Docker use case involves running eight containers per host, and that a quarter of analyzed organizations run 18 or more per host.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] It can also be installed on a single board computer like the Raspberry Pi.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] The Linux kernel's support for namespaces mostly isolates an application's view of the operating environment, including process trees, network, user IDs and mounted file systems, while the kernel's cgroups provide resource limiting for memory and CPU.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] Since version 0.9, Docker includes its own component (called libcontainer) to use virtualization facilities provided directly by the Linux kernel, in addition to using abstracted virtualization interfaces via libvirt, LXC and systemd-nspawn.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] Docker implements a high-level API to provide lightweight containers that run processes in isolation.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] , is a persistent process that manages Docker containers and handles container objects.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] The daemon listens for requests that are sent via the Docker Engine API.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] (CLI) that allows users to interact with Docker daemons.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] Docker objects are various entities used to assemble an application in Docker.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] The main classes of Docker objects are images, containers, and services.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] A Docker registry is a repository for Docker images.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] Docker clients connect to registries to download ("pull") images for use or upload ("push") images that they have built.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] Docker Hub is the default registry where Docker looks for images.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] Docker registries also allow the creation of notifications based on events.
[src:container-registry/docker-software] A Dockerfile is a text file that commonly specifies several aspects of a Docker container: the Linux distribution, installation commands for the programming language runtime environment and application source code.
[src:container-registry/open-container-initiative] The **Open Container Initiative** (**OCI**) is a Linux Foundation project, started in June 2015 by Docker, CoreOS, and the maintainers of appc (short for "App Container") to design open standards for operating system-level virtualization (containers).
[src:container-registry/open-container-initiative] At launch, OCI was focused on Linux containers and subsequent work has extended it to other operating systems.
[src:container-registry/open-container-initiative] There are currently three OCI specifications in development and use: the *Runtime Specification* (runtime-spec), the *Image Specification* (image-spec), and the *Distribution Specification* (distribution-spec).
[src:container-registry/open-container-initiative] The OCI Image Format Project was split out from the Runtime Project into its own specification on March 23, 2016.
[src:container-registry/open-container-initiative] The image-spec is a software shipping container image format spec (OCI Image Format) that reached version 1.0.0 on July 19, 2017.
[src:container-registry/open-container-initiative] The OCI Distribution Spec Project defines the distribution-spec, an API protocol to facilitate and standardize the distribution of content.
[src:container-registry/open-container-initiative] The distribution-spec was created on March 8, 2018, from a Proposal for a JSON Registry API V2.1.
[src:container-registry/open-container-initiative] The distribution-spec reached version 1.0.0 on April 26, 2021.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] A **software repository**, or **repo** for short, is a storage location for software packages.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Often a table of contents is also stored, along with metadata.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] A software repository is typically managed by source or version control, or repository managers.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Package managers allow automatically installing and updating repositories, sometimes called "packages".
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Many software publishers and other organizations maintain servers on the Internet for this purpose, either free of charge or for a subscription fee.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Repositories may be solely for particular programs, such as CPAN for the Perl programming language, or for an entire operating system.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Operators of such repositories typically provide a package management system, tools intended to search for, install and otherwise manipulate software packages from the repositories.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] For example, many Linux distributions use Advanced Packaging Tool (APT), commonly found in Debian based distributions, or Yellowdog Updater, Modified (yum) found in Red Hat based distributions.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] There are also multiple independent package management systems, such as pacman, used in Arch Linux and equo, found in Sabayon Linux.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] As software repositories are designed to include useful packages, major repositories are designed to be malware free.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] If a computer is configured to use a digitally signed repository from a reputable vendor, and is coupled with an appropriate permissions system, this significantly reduces the threat of malware to these systems.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] As a side effect, many systems that have these abilities do not need anti-malware software such as antivirus software.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Most major Linux distributions have many repositories around the world that mirror the main repository.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] At client side, a package manager helps installing from and updating the repositories.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] A package management system is different from a package development process.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] A typical use of a package management system is to facilitate the integration of code from possibly different sources into a coherent stand-alone operating unit.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Thus, a package management system might be used to produce a distribution of Linux, possibly a distribution tailored to a specific restricted application.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] A package development process, by contrast, is used to manage the co-development of code and documentation of a collection of functions or routines with a common theme, producing thereby a package of software functions that typically will not be complete and usable by themselves.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] A good package development process will help users conform to good documentation and coding practices, integrating some level of unit testing.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] The following table lists a few languages with repositories for contributed software.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] The "Autochecks" column describes the routine checks done.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Very few people have the ability to test their software under multiple operating systems with different versions of the core code and with other contributed packages they may use.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] For the R programming language, the Comprehensive R Archive Network (CRAN) runs tests routinely.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] To understand how this is valuable, imagine a situation with two developers, Sally and John.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Sally only runs the current version of the software under one version of Microsoft Windows, and has only tested it in that environment.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] At more or less regular intervals, CRAN tests Sally's contribution under a dozen combinations of operating systems and versions of the core R language software.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] If one of them generates an error, she gets that error message.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] With luck, that error message details may provide enough input to allow enable a fix for the error, even if she cannot replicate it with her current hardware and software.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Next, suppose John contributes to the repository a package B that uses a package A.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Package B passes all the tests and is made available to users.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Later, Sally submits an improved version of A, which breaks B.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] The autochecks make it possible to provide information to John so he can fix the problem.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] This example exposes both a strength and a weakness in the R contributed-package system: CRAN supports this kind of automated testing of contributed packages, but packages contributed to CRAN need not specify the versions of other contributed packages that they use.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Procedures for requesting specific versions of packages exist, but contributors might not use those procedures.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Beyond this, a repository such as CRAN running regular checks of contributed packages actually provides an extensive if *ad hoc* test suite for development versions of the core language.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] If Sally (in the example above) gets an error message she does not understand or thinks is inappropriate, especially from a development version of the language, she can (and often does with R) ask the core development-team for the language for help.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] In this way, the repository can contribute to improving the quality of the core language software.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Package managers help manage repositories and the distribution of them.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] If a repository is updated, a package manager will usually allow a user to update that repository through the manager.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] It also helps to manage things such as dependencies between other repositories.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] In an enterprise environment, a software repository is usually used to store artifacts, or to mirror external repositories which may be inaccessible due to security restrictions.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] One example is Sonatype Nexus Repository.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] At server side, a software repository is typically managed by source control or repository managers.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Some of the repository managers allow to aggregate other repository location into one URL and provide a caching proxy.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] When doing continuous builds many artifacts are produced and often centrally stored, so automatically deleting the ones which are not released is important.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] As part of the development lifecycle, source code is continuously being built into binary artifacts using continuous integration.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] This may interact with a binary repository manager much like a developer would by getting artifacts from the repositories and pushing builds there.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Artifacts and packages inherently mean different things.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Artifacts are simply an output or collection of files (ex.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] JAR, WAR, DLLS, RPM etc.) and one of those files may contain metadata (e.g.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Whereas packages are a single archive file in a well-defined format (ex.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] NuGet) that contain files appropriate for the package type (ex.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Many artifacts result from builds but other types are crucial as well.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Packages are essentially one of two things: a library or an application.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Compared to source files, binary artifacts are often larger by orders of magnitude, they are rarely deleted or overwritten (except for rare cases such as snapshots or nightly builds), and they are usually accompanied by much metadata such as id, package name, version, license and more.
[src:container-registry/software-repository] Metadata describes a binary artifact, is stored and specified separately from the artifact itself, and can have several additional uses.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The *Docker Registry HTTP API* is the protocol to facilitate distribution of images to the docker engine.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] It interacts with instances of the docker registry, which is a service to manage information about docker images and enable their distribution.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The specification covers the operation of version 2 of this API, known as *Docker Registry HTTP API V2*.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] While the V1 registry protocol is usable, there are several problems with the architecture that have led to this new version.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The main driver of this specification is a set of changes to the Docker image format, covered in docker/docker#8093.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The new, self-contained image manifest simplifies image definition and improves security.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] This specification will build on that work, leveraging new properties of the manifest format to improve performance, reduce bandwidth usage and decrease the likelihood of backend corruption.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] This specification covers the URL layout and protocols of the interaction between docker registry and docker core.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] This will affect the docker core registry API and the rewrite of docker-registry.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Docker registry implementations may implement other API endpoints, but they are not covered by this specification.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] While authentication and authorization support will influence this specification, details of the protocol will be left to a future specification.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Relevant header definitions and error codes are present to provide an indication of what a client may encounter.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] For the most part, the use cases of the former registry API apply to the new version.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Differentiating use cases are covered below.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] A docker engine instance would like to run verified image named “library/ubuntu”, with the tag “latest”.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The engine contacts the registry, requesting the manifest for “library/ubuntu:latest”.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] An untrusted registry returns a manifest.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Before proceeding to download the individual layers, the engine verifies the manifest’s signature, ensuring that the content was produced from a trusted source and no tampering has occurred.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] After each layer is downloaded, the engine verifies the digest of the layer, ensuring that the content matches that specified by the manifest.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Company X’s build servers lose connectivity to docker registry before completing an image layer transfer.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] After connectivity returns, the build server attempts to re-upload the image.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The registry notifies the build server that the upload has already been partially attempted.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The build server responds by only sending the remaining data to complete the image file.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Company X is having more connectivity problems but this time in their deployment datacenter.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] When downloading an image, the connection is interrupted before completion.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The client keeps the partial data and uses http `Range` requests to avoid downloading repeated data.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Company Y’s build system creates two identical docker layers from build processes A and B.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Build process A completes uploading the layer before B.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] When process B attempts to upload the layer, the registry indicates that its not necessary because the layer is already known.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If process A and B upload the same layer at the same time, both operations will proceed and the first to complete will be stored in the registry (Note: we may modify this to prevent dogpile with some locking mechanism).
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The V2 specification has been written to work as a living document, specifying only what is certain and leaving what is not specified open or to future changes.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Only non-conflicting additions should be made to the API and accepted changes should avoid preventing future changes from happening.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] This section should be updated when changes are made to the specification, indicating what is different.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Optionally, we may start marking parts of the specification to correspond with the versions enumerated here.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Each set of changes is given a letter corresponding to a set of modifications that were applied to the baseline specification.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] These are merely for reference and shouldn’t be used outside the specification other than to identify a set of modifications.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] This section covers client flows and details of the API endpoints.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The URI layout of the new API is structured to support a rich authentication and authorization model by leveraging namespaces.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] This scheme provides rich access control over various operations and methods using the URI prefix and http methods that can be controlled in variety of ways.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Classically, repository names have always been two path components where each path component is less than 30 characters.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The V2 registry API does not enforce this.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If a repository name has two or more path components, they must be separated by a forward slash ("/").
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The total length of a repository name, including slashes, must be less than 256 characters.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] These name requirements *only* apply to the registry API and should accept a superset of what is supported by other docker ecosystem components.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] All endpoints should support aggressive http caching, compression and range headers, where appropriate.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The new API attempts to leverage HTTP semantics where possible but may break from standards to implement targeted features.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] For detail on individual endpoints, please see the *Detail* section.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Actionable failure conditions, covered in detail in their relevant sections, are reported as part of 4xx responses, in a json response body.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The `code` field will be a unique identifier, all caps with underscores by convention.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The `message` field will be a human readable string.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The optional `detail` field may contain arbitrary json data providing information the client can use to resolve the issue.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] While the client can take action on certain error codes, the registry may add new error codes over time.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] All client implementations should treat unknown error codes as `UNKNOWN`, allowing future error codes to be added without breaking API compatibility.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] For the purposes of the specification error codes will only be added and never removed.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] For a complete account of all error codes, please see the *Errors* section.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] A minimal endpoint, mounted at `/v2/` will provide version support information based on its response statuses.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If a `200 OK` response is returned, the registry implements the V2(.1) registry API and the client may proceed safely with other V2 operations.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Optionally, the response may contain information about the supported paths in the response body.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The client should be prepared to ignore this data.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If a `401 Unauthorized` response is returned, the client should take action based on the contents of the “WWW-Authenticate” header and try the endpoint again.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Depending on access control setup, the client may still have to authenticate against different resources, even if this check succeeds.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If `404 Not Found` response status, or other unexpected status, is returned, the client should proceed with the assumption that the registry does not implement V2 of the API.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] When a `200 OK` or `401 Unauthorized` response is returned, the “Docker-Distribution-API-Version” header should be set to “registry/2.0”.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Clients may require this header value to determine if the endpoint serves this API.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] When this header is omitted, clients may fallback to an older API version.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] This API design is driven heavily by content addressability.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The core of this design is the concept of a content addressable identifier.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] It uniquely identifies content by taking a collision-resistant hash of the bytes.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Such an identifier can be independently calculated and verified by selection of a common *algorithm*.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If such an identifier can be communicated in a secure manner, one can retrieve the content from an insecure source, calculate it independently and be certain that the correct content was obtained.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Put simply, the identifier is a property of the content.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] To disambiguate from other concepts, we call this identifier a *digest*.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] A *digest* is a serialized hash result, consisting of a *algorithm* and *hex* portion.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The *algorithm* identifies the methodology used to calculate the digest.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The *hex* portion is the hex-encoded result of the hash.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] While the *algorithm* does allow one to implement a wide variety of algorithms, compliant implementations should use sha256.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Heavy processing of input before calculating a hash is discouraged to avoid degrading the uniqueness of the *digest* but some canonicalization may be performed to ensure consistent identifiers.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Above, we have bytestring `C` passed into a function, `SHA256`, that returns a bytestring `B`, which is the hash of `C`.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] `D` gets the algorithm concatenated with the hex encoding of `B`.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] We then define the identifier of `C` to `ID(C)` as equal to `D`.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] A digest can be verified by independently calculating `D` and comparing it with identifier `ID(C)`.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] To provide verification of http content, any response may include a `Docker-Content-Digest` header.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] This will include the digest of the target entity returned in the response.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] For blobs, this is the entire blob content.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] For manifests, this is the manifest body without the signature content, also known as the JWS payload.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Note that the commonly used canonicalization for digest calculation may be dependent on the mediatype of the content, such as with manifests.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The client may choose to ignore the header or may verify it to ensure content integrity and transport security.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] This is most important when fetching by a digest.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] To ensure security, the content should be verified against the digest used to fetch the content.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] At times, the returned digest may differ from that used to initiate a request.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Such digests are considered to be from different *domains*, meaning they have different values for *algorithm*.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] In such a case, the client may choose to verify the digests in both domains or ignore the server’s digest.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] To maintain security, the client *must* always verify the content against the *digest* used to fetch the content.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] An “image” is a combination of a JSON manifest and individual layer files.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The process of pulling an image centers around retrieving these two components.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The first step in pulling an image is to retrieve the manifest.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] For more information about the manifest format, please see docker/docker#8093.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] When the manifest is in hand, the client must verify the signature to ensure the names and layers are valid.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Once confirmed, the client will then use the digests to download the individual layers.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Layers are stored in as blobs in the V2 registry API, keyed by their digest.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The `name` and `reference` parameter identify the image and are required.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The reference may include a tag or digest.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The client should include an Accept header indicating which manifest content types it supports.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] For more details on the manifest format and content types, see Image Manifest Version 2, Schema 2.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] In a successful response, the Content-Type header will indicate which manifest type is being returned.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] A `404 Not Found` response will be returned if the image is unknown to the registry.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The client should verify the returned manifest signature for authenticity before fetching layers.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Layers are stored in the blob portion of the registry, keyed by digest.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Pulling a layer is carried out by a standard http request.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Access to a layer will be gated by the `name` of the repository but is identified uniquely in the registry by `digest`.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] This endpoint may issue a 307 (302 for <HTTP 1.1) redirect to another service for downloading the layer and clients should be prepared to handle redirects.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] This endpoint should support aggressive HTTP caching for image layers.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Support for Etags, modification dates and other cache control headers should be included.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] To allow for incremental downloads, `Range` requests should be supported, as well.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Pushing an image works in the opposite order as a pull.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] After assembling the image manifest, the client must first push the individual layers.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] When the layers are fully pushed into the registry, the client should upload the signed manifest.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The details of each step of the process are covered in the following sections.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] All layer uploads use two steps to manage the upload process.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The first step starts the upload in the registry service, returning a url to carry out the second step.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The second step uses the upload url to transfer the actual data.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Uploads are started with a POST request which returns a url that can be used to push data and check upload status.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The `Location` header will be used to communicate the upload location after each request.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] While it won’t change in this specification, clients should use the most recent value returned by the API.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The parameters of this request are the image namespace under which the layer will be linked.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Responses to this request are covered below.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The existence of a layer can be checked via a `HEAD` request to the blob store API.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If the layer with the digest specified in `digest` is available, a 200 OK response will be received, with no actual body content (this is according to http specification).
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] When this response is received, the client can assume that the layer is already available in the registry under the given name and should take no further action to upload the layer.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Note that the binary digests may differ for the existing registry layer, but the digests will be guaranteed to match.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The rest of the upload process can be carried out with the returned url, called the “Upload URL” from the `Location` header.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] All responses to the upload url, whether sending data or getting status, will be in this format.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Though the URI format (`/v2/<name>/blobs/uploads/<uuid>`) for the `Location` header is specified, clients should treat it as an opaque url and should never try to assemble it.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] While the `uuid` parameter may be an actual UUID, this proposal imposes no constraints on the format and clients should never impose any.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If clients need to correlate local upload state with remote upload state, the contents of the `Docker-Upload-UUID` header should be used.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Such an id can be used to key the last used location header when implementing resumable uploads.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The progress and chunk coordination of the upload process will be coordinated through the `Range` header.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] While this is a non-standard use of the `Range` header, there are examples of similar approaches in APIs with heavy use.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Note that the HTTP `Range` header byte ranges are inclusive and that will be honored, even in non-standard use cases.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] A monolithic upload is simply a chunked upload with a single chunk and may be favored by clients that would like to avoided the complexity of chunking.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The “digest” parameter must be included with the PUT request.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Please see the *Completed Upload* section for details on the parameters and expected responses.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] There is no enforcement on layer chunk splits other than that the server must receive them in order.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The server may enforce a minimum chunk size.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If this response is received, the client should resume from the “last valid range” and upload the subsequent chunk.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] For an upload to be considered complete, the client must submit a `PUT` request on the upload endpoint with a digest parameter.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If it is not provided, the upload will not be considered complete.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Optionally, if all chunks have already been uploaded, a `PUT` request with a `digest` parameter and zero-length body may be sent to complete and validate the upload.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Multiple “digest” parameters may be provided with different digests.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The server may verify none or all of them but *must* notify the client if the content is rejected.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The `Location` header will contain the registry URL to access the accepted layer file.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The `Docker-Content-Digest` header returns the canonical digest of the uploaded blob which may differ from the provided digest.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Most clients may ignore the value but if it is used, the client should verify the value against the uploaded blob data.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The “digest” parameter is designed as an opaque parameter to support verification of a successful transfer.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Given this parameter, the registry will verify that the provided content does match this digest.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] An upload can be cancelled by issuing a DELETE request to the upload endpoint.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] After this request is issued, the upload uuid will no longer be valid and the registry server will dump all intermediate data.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] While uploads will time out if not completed, clients should issue this request if they encounter a fatal error but still have the ability to issue an http request.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] A blob may be mounted from another repository that the client has read access to, removing the need to upload a blob already known to the registry.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] This behavior is consistent with older versions of the registry, which do not recognize the repository mount query parameters.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If an 502, 503 or 504 error is received, the client should assume that the download can proceed due to a temporary condition, honoring the appropriate retry mechanism.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Other 5xx errors should be treated as terminal.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If there is a problem with the upload, a 4xx error will be returned indicating the problem.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] After receiving a 4xx response (except 416, as called out above), the upload will be considered failed and the client should take appropriate action.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Note that the upload url will not be available forever.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If the upload uuid is unknown to the registry, a `404 Not Found` response will be returned and the client must restart the upload process.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] A layer may be deleted from the registry via its `name` and `digest`.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If the blob had already been deleted or did not exist, a `404 Not Found` response will be issued instead.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If a layer is deleted which is referenced by a manifest in the registry, then the complete images will not be resolvable.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Once all of the layers for an image are uploaded, the client can upload the image manifest.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The `name` and `reference` fields of the response body must match those specified in the URL.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The `reference` field may be a “tag” or a “digest”.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The content type should match the type of the manifest being uploaded, as specified in Image Manifest Version 2, Schema 2.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If there is a problem with pushing the manifest, a relevant 4xx response will be returned with a JSON error message.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Please see the *PUT Manifest* section for details on possible error codes that may be returned.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If one or more layers are unknown to the registry, `BLOB_UNKNOWN` errors are returned.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The `detail` field of the error response will have a `digest` field identifying the missing blob.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] An error is returned for each unknown blob.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Images are stored in collections, known as a *repository*, which is keyed by a `name`, as seen throughout the API specification.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] A registry instance may contain several repositories.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The list of available repositories is made available through the *catalog*.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Note that the contents of the response are specific to the registry implementation.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Some registries may opt to provide a full catalog output, limit it based on the user’s access level or omit upstream results, if providing mirroring functionality.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Subsequently, the presence of a repository in the catalog listing only means that the registry *may* provide access to the repository at the time of the request.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Conversely, a missing entry does *not* mean that the registry does not have the repository.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] More succinctly, the presence of a repository only guarantees that it is there but not that it is *not* there.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] For registries with a large number of repositories, this response may be quite large.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If such a response is expected, one should use pagination.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] A registry may also limit the amount of responses returned even if pagination was not explicitly requested.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] In this case the `Link` header will be returned along with the results, and subsequent results can be obtained by following the link as if pagination had been initially requested.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] For details of the `Link` header, please see the *Pagination* section.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Paginated catalog results can be retrieved by adding an `n` parameter to the request URL, declaring that the response should be limited to `n` results.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The above specifies that a catalog response should be returned, from the start of the result set, ordered lexically, limiting the number of results to `n`.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The above includes the *first* `n` entries from the result set.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] To get the *next* `n` entries, one can create a URL where the argument `last` has the value from `repositories[len(repositories)-1]`.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If there are indeed more results, the URL for the next block is encoded in an RFC5988 `Link` header, as a “next” relation.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The presence of the `Link` header communicates to the client that the entire result set has not been returned and another request must be issued.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If the header is not present, the client can assume that all results have been received.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Compliant client implementations should always use the `Link` header value when proceeding through results linearly.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The client may construct URLs to skip forward in the catalog.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The above process should then be repeated until the `Link` header is no longer set.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The catalog result set is represented abstractly as a lexically sorted list, where the position in that list can be specified by the query term `last`.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The entries in the response start *after* the term specified by `last`, up to `n` entries.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The behavior of `last` is quite simple when demonstrated with an example.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If the value of `n` is 2, *a* and *b* will be returned on the first response.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The client can then issue the request with the above value from the `Link` header, receiving the values *c* and *d*.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Note that `n` may change on the second to last response or be fully omitted, depending on the server implementation.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] It may be necessary to list all of the tags under a given repository.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] For repositories with a large number of tags, this response may be quite large.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If such a response is expected, one should use the pagination.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] Paginated tag results can be retrieved by adding the appropriate parameters to the request URL described above.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The behavior of tag pagination is identical to that specified for catalog pagination.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] We cover a simple flow to highlight any differences.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The above specifies that a tags response should be returned, from the start of the result set, ordered lexically, limiting the number of results to `n`.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The above process should then be repeated until the `Link` header is no longer set in the response.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] The behavior of the `last` parameter, the provided response result, lexical ordering and encoding of the `Link` header are identical to that of catalog pagination.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] An image may be deleted from the registry via its `name` and `reference`.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] For deletes, `reference` *must* be a digest or the delete will fail.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p01] If the image had already been deleted or did not exist, a `404 Not Found` response will be issued instead.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p02] The behavior of the endpoints are covered in detail in this section, organized by route and entity.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p02] All aspects of the request and responses are covered, including headers, parameters and body formats.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p02] Examples of requests and their corresponding responses, with success and failure, are enumerated.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p02] The detail for each endpoint is covered in the following sections.
[src:container-registry/spec-api-p02] Typically, this can be used for lightweight version checks and to validate registry authentication.
